    <title>Combined summary - Fork of invalid blocks due to BIP66 violations</title>
    <updated>2023-06-10T02:07:57.105486+00:00</updated>
    <link href="https://lists.linuxfoundation.org/pipermail/bitcoin-dev/2015-July/009340.html" rel="alternate"/>
    <summary>The conversations in the given context revolve around Simplified Payment Verification (SPV) mining, a method used by miners to mine blocks without verifying their validity completely. However, this method can be dangerous if used for an extended period. Invalid blocks are rare, so assuming a header is valid is the correct assumption. Still, miners should switch back to full mining after 20-30 seconds without fully validating the chain they are on for safety reasons. In various discussions and email exchanges, experts in the field of Bitcoin blockchain validation have explored ways to improve the efficiency and accuracy of blockchain validation. The use of fraud proofs to improve the situation of validating full nodes and SPV nodes has been suggested, with the possibility of producing fraud proofs in cases where blocks are invalid due to non-existent outputs or transaction data being withheld. The reliability of committed UTXO sets was also discussed, with suggestions made for ensuring their validity through source block references and extra commitments produced by miners.Additionally, there is a discussion about the violation of BIP66 by miners, which caused a rejection of the BIP by the network. A near majority of the hashrate on the network was SPV mining, leading to the potential for issues with software miners running custom patches that mine on top of the longest chain they know about, even if they haven't actually verified the blocks in it due to propagation delays. Measures need to be put in place to prevent such occurrences from happening again in the future.Finally, the need for implementing features such as node version checks and soft-fork codes for SPV clients was discussed. Overall, these discussions and exchanges highlight the ongoing efforts to improve the scalability and reliability of the Bitcoin blockchain through innovative solutions and collaboration among experts in the field.</summary>
